Set Operations? - Okasaari mee school syllabus ki veldhaam

"Set operations combine results of multiple SELECT queries"

JOIN -> combine columns of two or  more tables 
SET OPERATION  combine rows across multiple tables using Select

If JOIN is horizontal merging -> Set operations are vertical stacking (One by one rows)

Types of Set Operations in MySQL
MySQL officially supports:
1️.UNION
2️. UNION ALL

MySQL does NOT directly support:
3️. INTERSECT 
4️. EXCEPT 

But we can simulate them (I'll show you SPARK how)

employees(emp_id, name, team)
contractors(contract_id, name, team)

1. UNION
This set operator Combines results of two queries and removes duplicates records
Query: 
SELECT name FROM employees
UNION
SELECT name FROM contractors;

Usecases: - All unique names from both tables
- Duplicate records/rows will automatically removed

See this real Use Case 
HR wants:
Give me a list of all people working in the company (full-time + contractors)

Important Rules:
- Same number of columns (As it needs to combine within the same column in the stack(one-by-one way)
- Same data types
- Order of columns must match

2. UNION ALL
This set operator combines result  of rows but keeps duplicates

SELECT name FROM employees
UNION ALL
SELECT name FROM contractors;

- All rows stacked (Joined one -by-one)
- No duplicate removal ikada

Real Use Case:
- Finance report where duplicates matter
- Amazon return order will give a duplicate record again with same order_id

Performance Insight Entantee
- UNION ALL is faster than UNION
(because it does not remove duplicates)

In production, prefer UNION ALL unless deduplication is required

3. INTERSECT (Not Supported Directly in MySQL remeber SPARK)
Return only rows common in both queries.
Example (conceptually):
SELECT name FROM employees
INTERSECT
SELECT name FROM contractors; -- MySQL does not support this

Then How to Simulate INTERSECT
SELECT name FROM employees
WHERE name IN (
    SELECT name FROM contractors
);

OR idinaa

SELECT e.name
FROM employees e
JOIN contractors c ON e.name = c.name;

Real Use Case

Find people who:
Are both employees and contractors (data issue)
Exist in two systems

4️. EXCEPT (Not Supported Directly)
- Return rows in first query but NOT in second
SELECT name FROM employees
EXCEPT
SELECT name FROM contractors; -- Not supported in MySQL

How to Simulate EXCEPT
SELECT name
FROM employees
WHERE name NOT IN (
    SELECT name FROM contractors
);

OR (safer versionloo):

SELECT e.name
FROM employees e
LEFT JOIN contractors c
  ON e.name = c.name
WHERE c.name IS NULL; -- Find employees who are not contractors

 Operation  Removes Duplicates?  Supported in MySQL     Performance chudandi
 UNION      Yes               | Yes               | Slower      
 UNION ALL  No                | Yes               | Faster      
 INTERSECT  Yes               | No                | Simulated   
 EXCEPT     Yes               | No                | Simulated   

Common Fresher chesee Mistakes
- Column count mismatch
- Different data types
-- Using UNION instead of UNION ALL
- Using NOT IN with NULL values (dangerous)
-- Forgetting ORDER BY applies to final result only


Interview-Ready Answer

MySQL supports UNION and UNION ALL for combining result sets
UNION removes duplicates, while UNION ALL keeps them and performs better
MySQL does not directly support INTERSECT and EXCEPT, but they can be simulated using JOINs or subqueries
